# Design System Agent

## Auto-Detection

When working in any project, automatically check for design system documentation:

1. **Check for design system document:**
   - Look for `documents/design-system-[project-name].md` in the current project (where [project-name] is the folder name)
   - Also check for `documents/design-system-*.md` pattern
   - Alternative: `documents/design-system/README.md`
   - **Note:** All standard documents follow the pattern `[document-type]-[project-name].md` to avoid conflicts when working with multiple projects
   - If found, read and apply design system rules

2. **Context-aware application:**
   - Each project has its own unique design system
   - When in Plofti project → apply Plofti design system rules
   - When in minhaprimeiracnh project → apply minhaprimeiracnh design system rules
   - Rules adapt to the specific project's design system

## Rules Applied

When a design system is detected, always:

### 1. Use Design Tokens (Never Hardcode)

- **Always use CSS variables** for colors: `hsl(var(--primary))`, `bg-primary`, `text-foreground`
- **Always use Tailwind classes** that reference design tokens: `bg-primary`, `text-primary-foreground`
- **Never hardcode** colors: ❌ `bg-[#FBBF24]`, ❌ `color: #1F2933`
- **Never hardcode** fonts: ❌ `font-family: 'Inter'` (use `font-sans` if configured)
- **Never hardcode** spacing: ❌ `padding: 12px` (use Tailwind spacing scale)

### 2. Guide Component Creation

When creating or modifying components:

- **Check design system** for component patterns (buttons, inputs, cards, etc.)
- **Follow design system specifications** for component styling
- **Reference design system colors** from the palette
- **Use design system typography** hierarchy
- **Apply design system spacing** principles

### 3. Suggest Component Reuse

Before creating a new component:

- **Check existing components** in `src/components/` for similar functionality
- **Suggest reusing** existing components when appropriate
- **Suggest extending** existing components with variants rather than creating new ones
- **Look for shared components** that follow the design system

### 4. Verify Design System Compliance

When reviewing code:

- **Flag hardcoded values** that should use design tokens
- **Suggest design system alternatives** for non-compliant styling
- **Verify colors** match the design system palette
- **Verify typography** matches the design system hierarchy
- **Verify spacing** follows the design system scale

## Design System Structure Reference

When reading a design system document, extract:

- **Color palette:** Primary, secondary, background, foreground, supporting colors
- **Typography:** Font family, weights, hierarchy, line heights
- **Spacing:** Base unit, scale, layout principles
- **Components:** Button styles, input styles, card styles, icon styles
- **Visual principles:** Brand sensation, what to avoid, core visual rule

## Examples

### ✅ Correct Usage

```tsx
// Using design tokens
<Button className="bg-primary text-primary-foreground">
  Click me
</Button>

// Using Tailwind classes that reference design tokens
<div className="bg-background text-foreground p-4 rounded-lg">
  Content
</div>
```

### ❌ Incorrect Usage

```tsx
// Hardcoded colors
<Button className="bg-[#FBBF24] text-[#1F2933]">
  Click me
</Button>

// Hardcoded spacing
<div style={{ padding: '12px', color: '#1F2933' }}>
  Content
</div>
```

## Integration with Commands

- When `/create-design-system` is run, this rule will automatically apply the newly created design system
- When components are created, this rule guides them to follow the design system
- When code is reviewed, this rule flags non-compliance

## Important Notes

- Each project maintains its own unique design system
- Design system is the single source of truth for visual decisions
- All components must reference design tokens, never hardcoded values
- Design system ensures visual consistency across the entire product
